@victoriawill’s most successful images are the ones that make you feel something. Maybe you smile or look back at them again and again - there is something in them that resonate. Those images for her tend to have the combination of gesture, emotional connection and light.

It’s the light quality that marries them all together - whether it’s soft and subtle with a gentle kick or something bold and dynamic with a sharp source, without light the image would fall flat.

Head over to the 🔗 in bio & stories to watch full video and discover her honest and authentic imagery through light ⚡️

Sarah Gleaner is a long time friend of our family. This was taken almost 20 years ago at her place of employment. It was a book publisher that shutdown during Covid. Im revisiting some older work with fresh eyes and wanted to share her with you.

@littleleague 
Most people don't know that I was essentially raised at Memorial Stadium, watching the Baltimore Orioles season after season. Then I spent my teenage years at Camden Yards, learning independence and autonomy with 36,000 of my closest pals. Between @mlb and my brother's high school games, baseball was a constant. I learned the game inside and out. I would watch Baseball Tonight on @ESPN every night before bed, and my dad would wake me up in the morning with the sports page so I could catch the latest box scores and see what I missed from the late West Coast games. We had our own family calendar. Valentine's Day meant pitchers and catchers had to report. Spring Break was actually Spring Training. July 4th was the lead-up to the All-Star game. The beginning of school marked the post season.

Now I’m a parent watching my kids grow in skill and character at each Little League practice. Every week I’m struck by the passage of time from when I was learning the game until now. Much like Larry Sultan's work "Pictures from Home," I know I can't stop time, but I try to grieve its passing by making photos — photos that exist both as an artifact for my children to share in their joy, but also as a reminder to the maker that I am here now.

Here are a few from last week. I'm not sure they capture the complexity of what's in my head and heart each Saturday morning, but it's worth the exercise in discovery.
@murray.bartlett in my studio in BK. From the archives, but still a favorite.

I woke up thinking about this portrait I took of #joandidion in 2007. I always wished I had shot it another way — until recently. Now I love it exactly for what it is and for what it means to me and for what I learn from looking at it. (Not to mention the experience of being with her!) 

I didn’t trust myself or my point of view back then. I really wish I had. Now I see what I was doing and what I was aiming for. I really wish I hadn’t been so hard on myself. 

In Joan’s words, “Goodbye to all that.” 

She, of course, was referring to New York, but I’m talking about the juxtaposing thoughts in your head that fuel doubt and keep you from moving forward.
Portraits I made at @coach. I love it when then they street cast.
I’m really going to miss this moment in time. What a magical escape each episode has been. Thanks for letting me be a tiny fraction of a part in it. It will be a forever memory.

#lennybruce #lukekirby
The mind on this guy… and the size of his heart. Needless to say I admire how he uses both.

TGIF. 

Shooting here on a whim with one of my favorite collaborators who is always up for trying something and always seems to elevate even the most pedestrian ideas into something inspired.
Watching a team of passionate athletes and strong women like @trinity_rodman and the entire @uswnt is truly inspiring. Good Luck ladies!

There are some occasions where I have enough lead time on assignment to really dive into the research. 

On this one, to photograph @joelocke03 and @kit.connor from Netflix’s hit show @heartstopper I had just enough time to watch. And wow,  these young men, both 19, capture the raw essence of adolescence and the vulnerability that comes with self-discovery and young love. Their performances are tender and sincere. In person, they were equally as authentic. Their personal connection is clearly profound — how could it not be after such a shared experience. 

All this to say, I believe these young men have very bright futures and am grateful for their willingness to let me into their friendship for just an afternoon. I also hope they know how special this show is for everyone who is searching for themselves, but particularly for the LGTBQIA+ youth. 

Here are some outtakes. The story and other photos are on the @nytimes.
